Excess Antibiotics Before Cocci

This document summarizes estimates for unecessary antibiotics recieved before a diagnosis of coccidioidomycosis.

There were a total of R nrow(index_dates) patients with cocci who could be followed for at least one year prior to their index diagnosis.

We considered a R weekly_cp-week window prior to diagnosis as the diagnostic opportunity window where unecessary antibiotics associated with diagnostic delays may have been recieved.

The following plot depicts counts of the number of perscriptions each week before diagnosis, for each of the relevant antibiotic types

The following plot depicts expected trends for the number of antibiotics received based on data 14-52 weeks prior to diagnosis, using linear, quadratic and cubic trends.

The following plots depicts the number of antibiotics estimated to be in excess based on the expected trends depicted above.

Bootstrapping results

To estimate the number of excess antibiotics while accounting for uncertainty in the expected trend we utilized the following bootstrapping approach

  1. Draw a bootstrapped sample of patients
  2. Calculate the number of antibiotics each week
  3. Estimate expected trends over the 14-52 weeks prior to diagnosis for each trend type
  4. Compute the excess number of antibiotics as the difference between the observed number of antibiotics and the expected trend (extrapolated to the period between 1-13 weeks prior to diagnosis)

The above procedure was repeated 1000 times.

Patients Metrics for Reciept of Unecessary Antibiotics

In order to estimate the number of patients who recieved an unecessary antibiotic we performed the following bootstrapping-based analysis:

  1. Estimate the expected trend based on a bootstrapped sample of patients, and compute the estimated number of excess antibiotics (as described above).
  2. Return to the aggregate sample of patients; each week draw the estimated number of excess antibiotics by antibiotic type.
  3. Compute corresponding metrics and aggregate across trials.
